1
00:00:12,939 --> 00:00:15,223
Greetings, I hope you've had a fruitful day.

2
00:00:15,243 --> 00:00:17,725
I do not say happy, I say fruitful.

3
00:00:19,268 --> 00:00:42,676
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhodasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha

4
00:00:42,843 --> 00:00:49,009
Sam Buddha Sat, homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-awakened one.

5
00:00:52,231 --> 00:01:12,292
Some of you who get my email, get the news bite, might have got the news that they had a big meeting at five o'clock on Zoom to offer good wishes, prayers, et cetera, for Rob Bia, whom I think most of you know, huh?

6
00:01:12,311 --> 00:01:12,512
Yeah.

7
00:01:13,352 --> 00:01:20,902
So I'm hoping to mention him tonight when we do the business of compassion.

8
00:01:21,983 --> 00:01:24,927
Just bear with me a second so that I remember to do that.

9
00:01:28,790 --> 00:01:29,492
Hopefully I will.

10
00:01:31,034 --> 00:01:33,277
Never mind.

11
00:01:33,918 --> 00:01:41,807
So I did say that I would be...

12
00:01:42,513 --> 00:01:51,524
uh, approaching the, the, uh, the question about the Eightfold Noble Path, but I've been dragged, uh, back to, uh, contemplation of death.

13
00:01:51,623 --> 00:01:52,504
I hope you don't mind.

14
00:01:52,545 --> 00:01:55,828
It's always an absorbing topic, uh, for me.

15
00:01:55,909 --> 00:02:04,140
So I just want to read a letter, uh, sorry, an email that came concerning somebody who's been practicing this.

16
00:02:05,381 --> 00:02:07,924
Um, and this is what he says.

17
00:02:07,983 --> 00:02:08,604
He says, um,

18
00:02:10,103 --> 00:02:14,990
This morning, I managed to catch up with the talk on death and the virus, which I found intriguing.

19
00:02:16,132 --> 00:02:26,146
I followed it up with a 20-minute contemplation on the last breath, its powerful stuff, a quick way of generating a lot of unpleasant feelings.

20
00:02:27,549 --> 00:02:34,338
After 20 minutes, I decided to switch to metta, compassion practice for myself and others to balance the practice, the exercises.

21
00:02:35,483 --> 00:02:42,349
The feelings that came up in the death contemplation lingered through the morning and gave a certain edge to the day.

22
00:02:42,669 --> 00:02:43,390
Get that?

23
00:02:43,411 --> 00:02:45,894
An edge to the day, living in the moment.

24
00:02:47,435 --> 00:02:57,786
Now, in the afternoon, I went on a cycle ride and ended up doing a second death contemplation in a quiet local graveyard, the one about decay of the dead body.

25
00:02:57,806 --> 00:03:03,972
Now, that refers to the Satipatthana discourse especially,

26
00:03:04,777 --> 00:03:10,603
where in the body section, how to develop mindfulness of the body.

27
00:03:11,163 --> 00:03:21,813
The last section, of course, is the cemetery contemplations, where in those days, the bodies were just being laid out in the charnel grounds, eaten by animals, etc.

28
00:03:22,713 --> 00:03:30,782
And they were shrouded in white shroud, and the monks would take the cloth.

29
00:03:30,801 --> 00:03:34,465
I think this was a general habit for the Sramanas, for those who

30
00:03:34,681 --> 00:04:03,996
become uh become recluses of various different teachers uh to take that cloth and stitch it into robes you see and the buddha in that discourse uh really is is saying go and sit there and just watch that decomposition and you're supposed to be saying as this body is so mine will be that's that's pretty heavy no so anyway here he's i think he's referring to that um

31
00:04:04,717 --> 00:04:08,681
in a quiet local, and the one about decay of the dead body.

32
00:04:08,722 --> 00:04:09,681
So he's in the graveyard.

33
00:04:10,423 --> 00:04:13,066
And I found this one surprisingly easy.

34
00:04:14,426 --> 00:04:16,668
Maybe it was the ecologist's perspective.

35
00:04:17,088 --> 00:04:22,973
For me, there's something comforting about the realization that I'm going to end up as food for something else.

36
00:04:23,415 --> 00:04:24,255
Waste not, want not.

37
00:04:25,175 --> 00:04:27,257
I left the graveyard with a great sense of calm.

38
00:04:29,100 --> 00:04:34,725
Now that, of course, is the purpose of death meditation, or one of the purposes.

39
00:04:35,228 --> 00:04:45,800
is to having come to an acceptance of it, a growing, growing acceptance of it.

40
00:04:46,182 --> 00:04:54,372
Of course, we never know how much we've accepted the process of dying or the moment of death until we're actually doing it.

41
00:04:54,992 --> 00:04:59,718
But at least we can approach it, you see, and just take away its sting.

42
00:05:00,579 --> 00:05:02,281
Oh, death, where is thy sting?

43
00:05:05,062 --> 00:05:09,548
So I left the graveyard with a great sense of calm.

44
00:05:09,569 --> 00:05:19,740
So, and then his last paragraph, I will soon have more cause to observe and contemplate death and its effect on the living as a coffin bearer in a local gypsy funeral.

45
00:05:20,461 --> 00:05:26,209
Apparently it's becoming difficult to find four physically fit people who don't have to isolate themselves.

46
00:05:27,370 --> 00:05:33,298
There may be a whole new unexpected line of work opening up for me over the next few months.

47
00:05:34,199 --> 00:05:35,019
And may that be so.

48
00:05:36,129 --> 00:05:39,454
So there we have an email from somebody who's been practicing it.

49
00:05:39,653 --> 00:05:44,119
I would love to know that you have been practicing it and what effect it's had on you.

50
00:05:45,079 --> 00:05:53,949
For me, as I said, it was an enormously powerful practice in my youth, actually, in my 20s.

51
00:05:54,211 --> 00:05:56,913
That's when it sort of really hit me, this whole thing about death.

52
00:05:57,213 --> 00:06:00,076
Now, at that time, I was an annihilationist.

53
00:06:00,096 --> 00:06:02,279
I thought that when you die, that was the end of it.

54
00:06:02,319 --> 00:06:02,560
So

55
00:06:02,927 --> 00:06:09,336
My big question was a really silly question, really, was, you know, what was it like to go into nothingness?

56
00:06:09,978 --> 00:06:11,701
I mean, it would be like nothing, wouldn't it?

57
00:06:12,040 --> 00:06:17,389
But for some reason, it became an obsessive investigation.

58
00:06:18,569 --> 00:06:23,877
So definitely something to, you know, to practice.

59
00:06:24,197 --> 00:06:24,918
You'd have to do it.

60
00:06:25,180 --> 00:06:27,483
I mean, he did it for 20 minutes.

61
00:06:27,523 --> 00:06:29,526
That's quite a lengthy length of time.

62
00:06:29,877 --> 00:06:39,915
And if you want to do it on a regular basis, it can be just that few breaths where you remind yourself, you know, life is on a knife edge.

63
00:06:40,254 --> 00:06:45,725
And as I said, occasionally during the day to just acknowledge that the cup of tea is finished.

64
00:06:45,745 --> 00:06:46,065
That's it.

65
00:06:46,165 --> 00:06:47,769
You know, that's it.

66
00:06:47,829 --> 00:06:48,149
It's gone.

67
00:06:49,050 --> 00:06:49,831
There is no more.

68
00:06:49,891 --> 00:06:54,180
There's another cup of tea, but that cup of tea is completely gone.

69
00:06:56,404 --> 00:07:00,211
And the effect of that, of course, is to bring you into the present moment.

70
00:07:00,271 --> 00:07:03,254
That's the purpose of it, to live in the now.

71
00:07:03,295 --> 00:07:07,120
Whereas, for the most part, we're planning to live in the now.

72
00:07:07,281 --> 00:07:08,242
That's ridiculous, isn't it?

73
00:07:10,966 --> 00:07:17,254
And now I do want to follow up that, too, with the...

74
00:07:17,355 --> 00:07:18,516
This is the Anguttani, guys.

75
00:07:18,536 --> 00:07:19,137
See how big it is?

76
00:07:21,341 --> 00:07:23,204
You do some damage throwing this at somebody.

77
00:07:24,406 --> 00:07:25,247
So...

78
00:07:25,884 --> 00:07:42,903
I mentioned last night that the discourse I read was from the collection which was only extant in the Chinese and has been translated and is used by Bicuernalio.

79
00:07:42,923 --> 00:07:49,451
He seems to like those, probably to make us aware of them, really, and read them.

80
00:07:49,971 --> 00:07:55,538
But there are parallel discourses in the Theravada tradition

81
00:07:56,411 --> 00:08:10,569
So one of them is very much like that, except there's this slightly different way of doing it, you might say.

82
00:08:11,310 --> 00:08:20,360
So again, he's been through all these bhikkhus who tell him that they just want enough time

83
00:08:20,509 --> 00:08:25,776
to eat half of their alms food so that I may attend to the Blessed One's teaching.

84
00:08:26,096 --> 00:08:27,918
I could then accomplish much.

85
00:08:27,939 --> 00:08:40,572
So we could translate that these days, that you would only want to eat half of your alms meal or half of your meal so that you could practice spiritually.

86
00:08:42,195 --> 00:08:43,176
So you translate that.

87
00:08:44,134 --> 00:08:53,224
And then another one says, may I live just the time it takes to chew and swallow four or five mouthfuls of food so that I may attend to the Blessed One's teaching.

88
00:08:53,323 --> 00:08:54,605
I could then accomplish much.

89
00:08:55,466 --> 00:09:05,135
So they're always doing something in order to, they're always doing this thing, contemplation of death in order to listen to the Buddha's teachings.

90
00:09:05,635 --> 00:09:11,761
And as I say, we can translate that these days is in order to continue our spiritual practice.

91
00:09:12,215 --> 00:09:21,525
But at the end of the discourse, the Buddha delineates what in fact constitutes a proper contemplation of death using the similar image.

92
00:09:23,106 --> 00:09:29,073
The Bhikkhu, remember, refers to anybody who's listening or reading the scriptures, right?

93
00:09:31,256 --> 00:09:32,618
It's a figure of speech.

94
00:09:32,658 --> 00:09:33,940
I can't remember what it's called now.

95
00:09:34,000 --> 00:09:35,922
It's like when you say all hands on deck.

96
00:09:36,243 --> 00:09:38,144
We don't expect just the hands to turn up.

97
00:09:38,284 --> 00:09:38,424
Yeah.

98
00:09:40,716 --> 00:09:56,816
But the Bhikkhu who develops mindfulness of death thus, may I live just the length of time it takes to chew and swallow a single mouthful of food so that I may attend to the Buddha's teachings, the Blessed One's teachings.

99
00:09:57,115 --> 00:09:58,398
I could then accomplish much.

100
00:10:00,600 --> 00:10:03,364
He is one who develops mindfulness of death.

101
00:10:04,184 --> 00:10:04,625
Sorry.

102
00:10:04,644 --> 00:10:08,529
And there is one who develops the mindfulness of death thus.

103
00:10:09,184 --> 00:10:21,765
May I live just the length of time it takes to breathe out after breathing in and to breathe in after breathing out so that I may attend to the blessed one's teachings.

104
00:10:21,785 --> 00:10:27,095
And then he says, these I call bhikkhus who dwell heedfully.

105
00:10:28,056 --> 00:10:30,500
We could also say diligently.

106
00:10:30,519 --> 00:10:31,041
Yeah.

107
00:10:31,678 --> 00:10:44,073
I think the word being translated here, because I haven't been able to look up the Pali, is apamado, which is a very favourite word of the Buddha.

108
00:10:44,274 --> 00:10:50,520
It's one of his last, apamado sampadita, you know, strive diligently for your liberation.

109
00:10:52,043 --> 00:10:55,706
So that one is similar to the one that we read last night.

110
00:10:56,467 --> 00:11:01,533
But there's another one, which is a slightly different take.

111
00:11:02,087 --> 00:11:05,251
on mindfulness of death, you see.

112
00:11:07,895 --> 00:11:22,514
So he again tells the bhikkhus, mindfulness of death, when developed and cultivated, is of great benefit, of great fruit, culminating in the deathless, having the deathless as its consummation.

113
00:11:22,914 --> 00:11:25,518
The deathless is just another word for nirvana.

114
00:11:27,760 --> 00:11:30,745
So he says here, bhikkhus, when the day has receded,

115
00:11:31,518 --> 00:11:32,879
And night has approached.

116
00:11:33,541 --> 00:11:34,621
Habakkuk reflects thus.

117
00:11:35,783 --> 00:11:37,865
I could die on account of many causes.

118
00:11:38,407 --> 00:11:44,855
A snake might bite me, or a scorpion or centipede might sting me, and I might thereby die.

119
00:11:46,197 --> 00:11:47,599
That would be an obstacle to me.

120
00:11:47,899 --> 00:11:52,485
In other words, that's not good.

121
00:11:54,687 --> 00:11:59,313
I might stumble and fall, or my food might disagree with me.

122
00:12:00,086 --> 00:12:02,350
Or my bile might become agitated.

123
00:12:02,730 --> 00:12:05,134
My phlegm might become agitated.

124
00:12:05,455 --> 00:12:22,799
So remember, this was in those days where they had the four humors, the four temperaments, the melancholic, sad people, the choleric, the angry ones, the phlegmatic, the easygoing ones, and the sanguine, the happy ones.

125
00:12:22,820 --> 00:12:24,923
There's only one of the lot who are happy.

126
00:12:27,167 --> 00:12:27,967
Human miseries.

127
00:12:29,095 --> 00:12:35,480
And then he says sharp winds in the night might become agitated.

128
00:12:35,500 --> 00:12:37,142
So I don't know what that is.

129
00:12:37,922 --> 00:12:40,303
I did look up winds.

130
00:12:40,565 --> 00:12:42,807
It is part of a Chinese thing.

131
00:12:42,826 --> 00:12:54,275
But also I couldn't help coming across a medical journal which said this.

132
00:12:55,898 --> 00:12:58,679
While farting every day is normal,

133
00:12:59,268 --> 00:13:01,410
Farting all the time is not.

134
00:13:02,773 --> 00:13:04,515
We have excessive flatulence.

135
00:13:04,936 --> 00:13:09,842
You have excessive flatulence if you fart more than 20 times per day.

136
00:13:10,624 --> 00:13:17,914
In most cases, excessive farting can be controlled with changes to your diet and lifestyle.

137
00:13:17,934 --> 00:13:22,301
Okay, so I just thought I'd give you that little tidbit of good advice, okay?

138
00:13:26,706 --> 00:13:27,148
We can...

139
00:13:27,652 --> 00:13:36,261
And then finally said people might attack me and wild spirits might attack me and then I might die.

140
00:13:36,562 --> 00:13:40,846
So this would be a disadvantage because remember the preciousness of human life.

141
00:13:41,788 --> 00:13:50,577
The whole point about remaining a human being as long as we can is that this is the best place to to free ourselves from suffering.

142
00:13:53,360 --> 00:13:55,683
Now, then he says.

143
00:13:56,980 --> 00:14:16,201
Then when the Bhikkhu has reflected on the possibility of death during the night, he's then supposed to reflect and ask himself, do I have any bad unwholesome qualities that have not been abandoned, which might become an obstacle to me if I were to die tonight?

144
00:14:17,323 --> 00:14:22,870
If upon review the Bhikkhu knows I have bad unwholesome qualities that have not been abandoned,

145
00:14:23,355 --> 00:14:43,224
which might become an obstacle to me if I were to die tonight, then he should put forth extraordinary desire, effort, zeal, enthusiasm, indefatigability, untiringness, mindfulness and clear comprehension to abandon those bad, unwholesome qualities.

146
00:14:46,128 --> 00:14:48,672
Now, this actually reminds me of my own

147
00:14:49,192 --> 00:15:18,945
upbringing I think in most Christian circles you would go to bed with an examination of conscience that's what it was called in in in my particular form which was Catholicism and the idea was of course you'd look back over the day and see where you got angry where you got nasty where you got greedy and so on and so forth and of course you would you would ask for forgiveness for that and

148
00:15:19,177 --> 00:15:24,342
You can extend that, of course, to how you related to a sense of anxiety.

149
00:15:24,524 --> 00:15:26,225
Did you get caught up in it?

150
00:15:26,245 --> 00:15:27,306
Did you start getting panicky?

151
00:15:27,767 --> 00:15:29,248
Did you know what to do about that?

152
00:15:29,469 --> 00:15:39,678
So it's not just on a moral level, but the whole of our habits, the habitudes that we have, and to be aware of them when they come up.

153
00:15:39,698 --> 00:15:44,203
And then at the end of the day, we can reflect, well, I should have been quicker there.

154
00:15:44,705 --> 00:15:48,087
I could have been a bit more kinder there, et cetera, et cetera.

155
00:15:48,827 --> 00:15:51,953
And then made that determination, you see, tomorrow I will be.

156
00:15:53,296 --> 00:15:54,798
So that's what he says here.

157
00:15:54,818 --> 00:15:57,224
And then, of course, the opposite of that.

158
00:16:06,942 --> 00:16:11,510
He actually gives a nice little example, a nice little image here.

159
00:16:11,913 --> 00:16:27,192
The Buddha is always trying to match an intellectual understanding with some sort of imagery, some sort of imaginative way, because, as he says, some people think that way.

160
00:16:27,412 --> 00:16:33,419
Some people think in stories, in images, rather than a sort of straightforward intellectual manner.

161
00:16:33,960 --> 00:16:40,148
So he said that we should practice like that, just as one whose clothes or head had caught fire

162
00:16:40,634 --> 00:16:45,980
would put forth extraordinary desire, effort, zeal, and so on, to extinguish the fires.

163
00:16:47,501 --> 00:16:49,445
So somebody should do that, you see.

164
00:16:50,605 --> 00:16:58,534
Now, for somebody who doesn't have... Oh, yeah, excuse me.

165
00:17:01,318 --> 00:17:04,903
There's the opposite, of course.

166
00:17:05,423 --> 00:17:15,997
But upon review, the bhikkhu knows I do not have any bad unwholesome qualities that have not been abandoned, which might become an obstacle for me if I were to die tonight.

167
00:17:16,356 --> 00:17:24,208
Then the Buddha says he should dwell in the same rapture and joy, training night and day in wholesome qualities.

168
00:17:24,228 --> 00:17:26,770
So remember the wholesome qualities.

169
00:17:26,790 --> 00:17:28,093
We can also reflect on that.

170
00:17:28,173 --> 00:17:32,337
We don't have to be completely free of unwholesome qualities.

171
00:17:32,397 --> 00:17:35,261
We can reflect on the wholesome qualities that we

172
00:17:35,545 --> 00:17:40,771
expressed during the day and determine that we will continue to develop them.

173
00:17:41,834 --> 00:17:46,401
All these mental states can be developed indefinitely, right?

174
00:17:46,421 --> 00:17:51,027
You can become as evil as evil and become as beautiful as beautiful.

175
00:17:51,528 --> 00:17:57,215
Mentally beautiful, of course, heart beautiful.

176
00:17:58,411 --> 00:18:07,403
And then, as always, these scriptures, they're not only repetitive, but they also, as it were, reinforce.

177
00:18:08,224 --> 00:18:11,229
By being repetitive, they reinforce the teaching.

178
00:18:11,608 --> 00:18:16,977
So just as we started off by saying, when day has receded and night has approached.

179
00:18:17,376 --> 00:18:22,964
So the final paragraph is, when night has receded and day has approached.

180
00:18:22,984 --> 00:18:25,749
So again, it's that recollection in the morning.

181
00:18:26,150 --> 00:18:26,410
Yeah.

182
00:18:30,253 --> 00:18:30,753
Very good.

183
00:18:30,934 --> 00:18:34,038
So I think we can put death to bed for a little while.

184
00:18:37,300 --> 00:18:46,368
But I would love to hear from you if you happen to practice and just see if it did have a beneficial effect on your life, on your sense of awareness.

185
00:18:50,752 --> 00:18:56,699
So I had a question about, we can move on, yeah?

186
00:18:57,740 --> 00:18:58,480
Yes, I've got that.

187
00:18:59,000 --> 00:18:59,181
Good.

188
00:19:00,071 --> 00:19:04,258
So we can move on to a question that came through about how to live frugally.

189
00:19:04,298 --> 00:19:18,519
Many people now have found themselves without work, either because the firm has dismissed its workers or you've been furloughed.

190
00:19:18,701 --> 00:19:20,242
This is a new word for me, furloughed.

191
00:19:20,343 --> 00:19:21,084
I don't quite know.

192
00:19:21,684 --> 00:19:27,513
It just means that you're still employed by the firm, but you're not being paid.

193
00:19:29,806 --> 00:19:36,272
And many of you know Carl, Carl Fuchs, who teaches here.

194
00:19:36,712 --> 00:19:41,538
So he works for the Department of Work and Pensions.

195
00:19:41,838 --> 00:19:50,387
And the amount of people applying now for the Dole, what we call the Dole, is enormous.

196
00:19:51,588 --> 00:19:54,652
So you may find yourself in that position, of course.

197
00:19:54,692 --> 00:19:57,535
And the question is how to live frugally.

198
00:20:01,092 --> 00:20:11,446
I think it's good to remember that, you know, we weren't always, the society wasn't always as rich as it has been over these past 20, 25 years.

199
00:20:12,048 --> 00:20:18,115
Even after the 2008 crash, unemployment stayed pretty high.

200
00:20:18,155 --> 00:20:21,601
The bulk of people did get decent wages.

201
00:20:21,661 --> 00:20:22,623
I'm sorry about the West now.

202
00:20:23,723 --> 00:20:25,826
Or should we say the rich countries in the West.

203
00:20:28,431 --> 00:20:30,693
But it's not that long ago.

204
00:20:31,130 --> 00:20:40,544
I mean, World War II, rationing was there for 14 years from the beginning of the war to, I've got the date here, 4th of July, 1954.

205
00:20:41,926 --> 00:20:50,259
And that was when food rationing came to an end, when restrictions on the sale of the purchase of meat and bacon was lifted.

206
00:20:51,141 --> 00:20:59,212
It was 14 years of people having to be careful, were limited in what they could eat.

207
00:21:03,057 --> 00:21:07,443
And as a child, of course, I would have been a child then, born in 47.

208
00:21:07,765 --> 00:21:09,186
I'd been about seven years old.

209
00:21:10,829 --> 00:21:12,011
You don't know.

210
00:21:12,031 --> 00:21:14,656
You're not aware of being poor or not poor.

211
00:21:16,539 --> 00:21:21,347
But in those days, you know, you've got to clip around the ear if you left the light on.

212
00:21:21,729 --> 00:21:25,535
If you broke a cup, yeah, your dad would be on to you.

213
00:21:25,555 --> 00:21:26,317
That costs money.

214
00:21:26,537 --> 00:21:27,178
You know what I mean?

215
00:21:27,198 --> 00:21:27,798
It's sort of bad.

216
00:21:28,318 --> 00:21:30,041
It's not going to jump at you.

217
00:21:30,061 --> 00:21:43,742
And I do remember my aunties, you know, when we used to go and visit, you get a piece of bread and the jam on it was, well, you wouldn't say there was any jam on it.

218
00:21:44,183 --> 00:21:49,291
There was a touch of jam sort of expressing itself on the bread.

219
00:21:49,311 --> 00:21:55,862
I remember cucumber sandwiches, really thin, thin little pieces of cucumber.

220
00:21:57,007 --> 00:22:00,490
So you don't have to die because you're going to be frugal.

221
00:22:02,231 --> 00:22:06,836
Just in my own case, there was a period there in the 80s when I was unemployed and I was on the dole.

222
00:22:07,317 --> 00:22:12,101
And I just remember by that time I was practicing.

223
00:22:12,342 --> 00:22:16,305
I was into Buddhism, so I wasn't drinking at that time or anything like that.

224
00:22:16,865 --> 00:22:21,289
And I remember, you know, I handled it well.

225
00:22:21,309 --> 00:22:26,575
Well, I was rather lucky, really, because I went to live in a lodging where

226
00:22:27,060 --> 00:22:30,384
they allowed me just to make a donation, basically.

227
00:22:30,846 --> 00:22:31,846
I was very fortunate.

228
00:22:34,150 --> 00:22:42,540
And I remember eating a lot of awful, you know, liver and kidney and beginning to feel a bit ill about it.

229
00:22:42,560 --> 00:22:45,404
It was about that time I decided to go vegetarian.

230
00:22:46,306 --> 00:22:49,430
But there wasn't much on the market then for vegetarian food.

231
00:22:50,692 --> 00:22:56,680
And I just got used to, you know, living frugally.

232
00:22:56,980 --> 00:23:02,146
So you can't go out and just buy stuff, as you might have done at one point, one time.

233
00:23:02,887 --> 00:23:04,048
You just live simply.

234
00:23:05,631 --> 00:23:06,952
And, of course, we've forgotten that.

235
00:23:07,272 --> 00:23:10,877
There's a whole generation that have forgotten how to live frugally.

236
00:23:12,700 --> 00:23:18,366
Even, you know, as a child, I remember waking up in the morning.

237
00:23:18,386 --> 00:23:20,529
There was no heat in the house.

238
00:23:20,549 --> 00:23:23,493
You know, the old man had to go downstairs and build a fire.

239
00:23:23,534 --> 00:23:25,856
And on weekends, I'd be down there with him.

240
00:23:26,191 --> 00:23:54,003
screwing up paper and putting coal on top uh and you'd get up in the freeze especially winter there'd be ice on the window and you didn't bother you just got up you washed your face you went down and the kitchen was the only place that was warm and you know they had three kids three of us sort of bundling in there and uh and making a bit of a row and that was the only warm place the kitchen uh by evening course they mum had um

241
00:23:54,321 --> 00:23:55,784
you know, built the fire and all that.

242
00:23:56,023 --> 00:23:57,365
So it was a bit more pleasant.

243
00:23:57,926 --> 00:24:04,095
But central heating for us didn't come until the mid-60s and for many came in much later.

244
00:24:05,517 --> 00:24:08,260
So you can get used to a situation.

245
00:24:08,280 --> 00:24:09,261
You can get used to that.

246
00:24:09,282 --> 00:24:10,884
I mean, it's the same as coming on retreat.

247
00:24:11,045 --> 00:24:12,866
You change all your habits.

248
00:24:13,107 --> 00:24:15,330
I mean, it's difficult, first two or three days, and that's it.

249
00:24:17,493 --> 00:24:23,501
I mean, the horror story for me, of course, would be, well, as you know, no toast, but worse.

250
00:24:23,683 --> 00:24:27,950
Worse, no soya milk or oatly to put in my tea.

251
00:24:28,471 --> 00:24:32,016
I mean, that brings up almost a panicky sort of feeling.

252
00:24:36,663 --> 00:24:41,650
And I remember, too, you know, kids coming to school with no socks and things like that, a bit scruffy.

253
00:24:43,112 --> 00:24:46,016
Even though they had, you had three changes.

254
00:24:46,076 --> 00:24:48,921
You had one for your ordinary messing about clothes.

255
00:24:49,040 --> 00:24:51,884
You had your school uniform, if your parents could afford it.

256
00:24:52,709 --> 00:24:53,950
And you had your Sunday best.

257
00:24:54,171 --> 00:24:54,570
That was it.

258
00:24:55,172 --> 00:24:56,313
I remember being a student.

259
00:24:56,333 --> 00:24:58,255
I only had, I think, two or three shirts.

260
00:24:59,376 --> 00:25:04,603
So, you know, it's like realizing that you don't need all this.

261
00:25:07,766 --> 00:25:13,692
How can we approach a situation where we find we don't have the money that we used to have?

262
00:25:14,894 --> 00:25:21,281
And it really is just drawing up a list of what you actually need, right, as opposed to want.

263
00:25:21,801 --> 00:25:25,224
which might not be particularly greedy.

264
00:25:26,026 --> 00:25:31,230
You might want another shirt or another piece of dress.

265
00:25:32,290 --> 00:25:34,292
But when you look around, you don't need it.

266
00:25:34,313 --> 00:25:37,115
And it's just really bring yourself down to need.

267
00:25:37,776 --> 00:25:42,680
Now, for the monastic life, the Buddha had these, what we call the four requisites.

268
00:25:43,280 --> 00:25:44,981
And you had to be happy with what you were given.

269
00:25:45,222 --> 00:25:46,083
This is the idea.

270
00:25:46,103 --> 00:25:51,268
And in those days, you often ended up with the very simplest of things.

271
00:25:51,586 --> 00:25:58,238
So, for instance, we're supposed to be happy with whatever is put into the bowl.

272
00:25:59,299 --> 00:26:04,469
And I remember when I was in Thailand once, we went out to the villages.

273
00:26:04,950 --> 00:26:06,511
And when we came back, there was only rice.

274
00:26:06,873 --> 00:26:09,657
Very poor, extremely poor, just a bit of rice.

275
00:26:09,718 --> 00:26:14,326
And I think they put in a bit of the fish to get out of the ponds.

276
00:26:15,248 --> 00:26:16,529
It wasn't fish, it was something else.

277
00:26:17,928 --> 00:26:19,210
which I won't forget, frankly.

278
00:26:20,351 --> 00:26:28,122
But luckily, when we got back to the monastery, the middle class from the towns had brought some delicious food.

279
00:26:28,803 --> 00:26:44,664
But if I had lived deep into the places in Thailand at that time, so going back to, again, late 80s, you've had to be happy with just rice.

280
00:26:44,684 --> 00:26:47,209
So that was the first thing.

281
00:26:47,459 --> 00:26:51,546
uh, for, for, um, shelter.

282
00:26:52,066 --> 00:26:52,646
That's another thing.

283
00:26:52,666 --> 00:26:53,628
So you need shelter.

284
00:26:53,648 --> 00:26:59,979
You need the four basic requisites are food, shelter, um, clothing and medicine.

285
00:26:59,999 --> 00:27:01,382
I mean, that's what the body needs, right?

286
00:27:01,402 --> 00:27:04,406
We're not talking about what the heart or the mind is, but what the body needs.

287
00:27:04,527 --> 00:27:04,906
That's all.

288
00:27:06,028 --> 00:27:13,221
So, uh, and when it came to shelter was just to be happy in, you know, a root of a tree or to build yourself a temporary shelter.

289
00:27:14,502 --> 00:27:14,563
Um,

290
00:27:17,412 --> 00:27:21,778
Later on, monasteries were built for the Buddha, so they became a bit more flashy, you know.

291
00:27:22,720 --> 00:27:27,086
But you're just to be happy with the place you're living in, basically.

292
00:27:27,788 --> 00:27:34,637
Now, you know, having said that, we know that there are people out there on the streets, and that's, of course, an abomination, frankly, for a rich country.

293
00:27:35,179 --> 00:27:36,039
Absolute abomination.

294
00:27:38,143 --> 00:27:39,105
And then there's clothing.

295
00:27:39,826 --> 00:27:46,035
Now, the clothing is just to protect the body from heat, from in those –

296
00:27:46,369 --> 00:27:50,875
in India from flies and gadflies and mosquitoes and stuff like that.

297
00:27:51,255 --> 00:27:53,577
And of course, for modesty's sake.

298
00:27:53,978 --> 00:28:01,546
But that's your basic need is to clothe the body so it doesn't get cold in this country anyway.

299
00:28:01,566 --> 00:28:04,108
It doesn't matter what you're actually wearing, does it?

300
00:28:04,229 --> 00:28:05,450
As long as it keeps you warm.

301
00:28:06,951 --> 00:28:08,573
I mean, it doesn't have to be fashionable.

302
00:28:10,295 --> 00:28:12,057
And finally, medicine.

303
00:28:12,948 --> 00:28:22,443
In those days, you had to be, what the scripture says, the Buddha says is that you have to be happy with fermented cow's urine.

304
00:28:23,105 --> 00:28:24,448
Now, frankly, I never tried it.

305
00:28:24,827 --> 00:28:26,692
I never got around to doing that.

306
00:28:26,711 --> 00:28:30,557
And I'm not so sure anybody else has since those times.

307
00:28:31,138 --> 00:28:33,403
But obviously, that was considered to be a medicine.

308
00:28:34,192 --> 00:28:37,959
And, yeah, just happy with the medicine that comes.

309
00:28:38,299 --> 00:28:45,271
Now, it might be, you see, that you end up with the NHS with a minor or serious complaint, serious disease.

310
00:28:46,113 --> 00:28:53,326
And we know it's actually being, you know, so heavily used.

311
00:28:53,645 --> 00:28:55,950
It's a breaking point constantly.

312
00:28:56,049 --> 00:28:58,934
The nurses, the doctors have been completely overworked.

313
00:28:59,489 --> 00:29:05,056
And so you might find yourself not being treated well or not being treated for quite some time.

314
00:29:05,116 --> 00:29:08,461
And, you know, you have to accept that.

315
00:29:08,601 --> 00:29:11,744
There's no point in sort of getting angry about it.

316
00:29:12,326 --> 00:29:13,567
That doesn't do anything, does it?

317
00:29:14,449 --> 00:29:17,633
Anxiety will be there, of course, if you feel you have something serious.

318
00:29:19,095 --> 00:29:20,897
But that's basically what you have to accept.

319
00:29:21,818 --> 00:29:24,702
Fermented cow's urine, right?

320
00:29:25,503 --> 00:29:26,424
I'm sure it's good for you.

321
00:29:28,835 --> 00:29:33,179
So thinking about frugality, seeing what the need is.

322
00:29:33,219 --> 00:29:39,243
When it comes to the heart-mind, really to keep the mind active, to keep feeding it.

323
00:29:39,304 --> 00:29:43,807
Now, these days, there's so much free materials on the websites.

324
00:29:45,368 --> 00:29:47,310
It really doesn't have to cost you anything.

325
00:29:48,832 --> 00:29:55,317
Free book downloads from, what is it, the Gutenberg Project on Google, things like that.

326
00:29:55,817 --> 00:29:57,880
And of course, there's

327
00:29:58,281 --> 00:30:00,785
There are still, I believe, one or two libraries around.

328
00:30:01,726 --> 00:30:04,911
And of course, conversation, good conversation with friends.

329
00:30:06,653 --> 00:30:11,098
And the heart needs also, you know, to be nourished.

330
00:30:12,079 --> 00:30:20,371
There's not just the social virtues of, you know, compassion, love and all that, conversation with people, but art, art and nature.

331
00:30:21,791 --> 00:30:26,077
We need that sort of feed, you know,

332
00:30:26,632 --> 00:30:43,493
I mean, it's one of those things that monasteries, the meditation monasteries, are often a way out in the forests to get out there away from the city jungle and into a beautiful place.

333
00:30:44,255 --> 00:30:48,121
So one has to accept that as part of a frugality.

334
00:30:48,161 --> 00:30:55,170
Now, in the old days, you might have done all sorts of things that cost money, but there's plenty of stuff out there that wouldn't cost anything.

335
00:30:58,238 --> 00:31:02,249
So it's looking after the body, principally, of course, because you can't be here without one.

336
00:31:03,151 --> 00:31:07,843
And then taking care of the heart, mind, culture, all that sort of stuff.

337
00:31:07,863 --> 00:31:14,661
So in this way, we can live with frugal times.

338
00:31:24,563 --> 00:31:29,550
Yes, and I put here, and the least costly of all, of course, is spiritual practice.

339
00:31:29,570 --> 00:31:34,357
All you need is the space of your own body and sit down and carry on.

340
00:31:39,645 --> 00:31:47,617
So I hope that these little hints, I always like to have some feedback.

341
00:31:48,900 --> 00:31:53,727
If you're doing the actual practices, feedback about what your thoughts are.

342
00:31:53,960 --> 00:32:02,809
Email, please, because I don't actually read this stuff coming down.

343
00:32:02,890 --> 00:32:05,459
I can't speak and read it.

344
00:32:05,779 --> 00:32:06,742
There's a lot coming through.

345
00:32:09,311 --> 00:32:11,479
Julie here says there's a detailed description.

